	- @use vs @import
		- the @use rule is intended to replace the old @import rule, but it's intentionally designed to work differently
		- [Use vs Import in Sass: Which One Should You Choose?](https://kentwynn.com/frontend-languages/use-vs-import-in-sass-which-one-should-you-choose/kentwynn/27/03/2023) (March 2023)
			- you have two options: @use and @import. While both options have their advantages, @use is generally recommended over @import
			- by using @use, you can avoid naming conflicts, improve performance, and make your code clearer and more maintainable
			- with @use, you can also specify an alias for the module or file you are importing, which can help avoid naming conflicts
			- while @import is still supported in Sass, it is being phased out in favor of @use
				- reason: @use provides better control over namespace and the ability to specify specific pieces of code to import
				- if you are starting a new project or updating an existing one, it’s recommended to use @use instead of @import in your Sass code
		- Kevin Powell [Stop using @import with Sass | @use and @forward explained](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CR-a8upNjJ0)
			- @use and @forward are part of the new module system
			- 2021 "import is being deprecated"
			- everything is namespaced now:##everythingnames
			- when we use @use, it is only available inside that file
			- his setup##hisesetup
			- @use is to import it to use it in that file
			- @forward is to import it to send it back out
			- you can use letter or *##oneletterorstar
			- if you call the file index, you only need to list the folder
		- [Node-Sass or Dart-Sass : The CSS Preprocessor Dilemma](https://itnext.io/the-css-preprocessor-dilemma-node-sass-or-dart-sass-32a0a096572)
			- when you run the command **npm i sass**, you are installing **Dart Sass**
				- the **sass** package on npm is the official **[Dart Sass](https://sass-lang.com/dart-sass)** implementation 
				- the predecessor was **npm i node-sass** which is referred to as Node Sass
				- the node-sass project has been deprecated, and the official recommendation is to use Dart Sass
			- @foward seems to be a kind of export
		- [@use & @forward in SASS ](https://dev.to/mr_ali3n/use-forward-in-sass-2bab)
			- nnn
		- [Sass @import is being replaced with @use and @forward](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dOnYNEXv9BM)
			- her imports look like this:##hasmainandimpo
			- shows why @include has problems, e.g. variables are overwritten if they have the same name
			- shows if you move the order over loading files, it doesn't work
			- Sass is moving to **[Sass modules](https://css-tricks.com/introducing-sass-modules)** is the new approach
			- you have to import modules like list and map##canimportmath
			- when using the @use rule in Sass, you are not required to use underscores in file names
				- the use of underscores in file names is a convention often associated with the older @import rule
			- the file is only imported once, no matter how many times you @use it in a project
			- variables, mixins, and functions (what Sass calls "members") that start with an underscore (_) or hyphen (-) are considered private, and not imported.
				- members from the used file (buttons.scss in this case) are only made available locally, but not passed along to future imports
				- @extends will only apply up the chain; extending selectors in imported files, but not extending files that import this one
				- all imported members are namespaced by default
		- [The New SASS Module System: Out with @import, In with @use](https://stefaniefluin.medium.com/the-new-sass-module-system-out-with-import-in-with-use-e1bd8ba032d0) - 2020
			- suggested structure##suggestedStructure
			- numbers are to keep folders in order
			- I import the 3-helpers files using @use which then lets me freely use the color variables from the _constants.scss file
			- [@mixin and @include](https://sass-lang.com/documentation/at-rules/mixin)
			- Mixin names, like all Sass identifiers, treat hyphens and underscores as identical
